In [6]:
def string_to_wordlist(raw_review, remove_stopwords=False, lemmatize=False):

    #remove punctuation.
    letters_only = re.sub('[^a-zA-Z]', ' ', raw_review)

    #lower case and split.
    words = letters_only.lower().split()

    #remove stopwords if wanted.
    if remove_stopwords:
        stops = set(stopwords.words("german"))
        words = [w for w in words if not w in stops]

    #lemmatize words for better model quality.
    if lemmatize:
        lemmatizer = Cistem()
        words = [lemmatizer.segment(word)[0] for word in words]

    return words
In [7]:
tokenizer = nltk.data.load("tokenizers/punkt/german.pickle")

def string_to_sentence(review, remove_stopwords=False, lemmatize=False):

    #review to sentence
    raw_sentences = tokenizer.tokenize(review.strip())

    #loop over sentences
    sentences= []
    for raw_sentence in raw_sentences:
        if len(raw_sentence)>0:
            sentences.append(string_to_wordlist(raw_sentence, lemmatize, remove_stopwords))

    return sentences

# Tag all Hesse books.
book_names = [name[:-4].strip('./hesse ').lower() for name in glob.glob('./hesse/*txt')]
hesse_tag_df = pd.DataFrame([], columns=['words','tags','book'])
for name, book in zip(book_names, book_list):

    print(f'Tagging {name}...')
    t = tagger.tag(re.sub('[^a-zA-Z]', ' ', book).split())

    frame = pd.DataFrame(list(zip(*t))).T
    frame.columns = ['words','tags']
    frame = frame.assign(book=name)

    hesse_tag_df = hesse_tag_df.append(frame)

hesse_tag_df = hesse_tag_df.assign(tag_agg = hesse_tag_df.tags.map(rename_mask))
hesse_tag_df.reset_index(drop=True,inplace=True)

Rolling sum over grammar count¶

In [18]:
def plot_grammar(document, struk, window_size):

    gram_s = pd.Series(np.where(document.tag_agg.values == struk,1,0))
    gram_s.rolling(window_size, min_periods=1, center=True).sum().plot(kind='line')
    plt.title(struk)

# Func to collect the grammar window count for a grammatic structure.
# Returns a Series that can later be collected in a DF.
def grammar_window(document, struk):
    return pd.Series(np.where(document.tag_agg.values == struk,1,0)) \
               .rolling(500, min_periods=500, center=True).sum()

Word Embeddings¶

In [ ]:
import numpy as np

def loadEmbeddingModel(File):
    print("Loading Glove Model")
    f = open(File,'r')
    gloveModel = {}
    for i,line in enumerate(f):
        splitLines = line.split()
        word = eval(splitLines[0]).decode('utf-8')
        wordEmbedding = np.array([float(value) for value in splitLines[1:]])
        gloveModel[word] = wordEmbedding
        if i%100000==0: print(f'Progress #: {i}')
    print(len(gloveModel)," words loaded!")
    return gloveModel

##Func to turn word vec into the closest word.
import heapq
from sklearn.metrics.pairwise import cosine_similarity
def most_similar(v, N=10):
    sims = vecs.values.dot(v)
    #sims = cosine_similarity(vecs.values, vecs.loc[w].values.reshape(1,-1))
    sims = heapq.nlargest(N, zip(sims,vecs.index.values))

    return sims

%%time
#Check for every word in book, if it is closed to "good" of "bad" word vector, to
#get the positive or negative connotation of the word as the difference between
#the two vectors. Naive appoach, but worth a try.
sentiments=[]
siddharta = book_list[-1] #Look at Siddharta from Hesse because I know the book well.
gut = embeddingMat['gut'].reshape(1,-1)
schlecht = embeddingMat['schlimm'].reshape(1,-1)

for w in string_to_wordlist(siddharta):
    sim_gut, sim_schlecht = cosine_similarity(embeddingMat[w].reshape(1,-1), gut),\
                            cosine_similarity(embeddingMat[w].reshape(1,-1), schlecht)
    diff = sim_gut-sim_schlecht
    sentiments.append(diff)

The sentiment cumsum is rising linearly and doesnt show a significant change chapterwise. No statement about the general sentiment about parts of a book can be made this way. The rolling window shows beautiful ups and downs that might correspond to the book's actual sentiment.

    return re.search('\w+(?=|)', string)[0]

def sentiment_to_csv(path, book):
    sentiments = [sentMap[w] if w in mapKeys else 0 \
                  for w in string_to_wordlist(book)]
    roll = pd.Series(sentiments).rolling(500, min_periods=100).sum()
    roll.to_csv(path)
